          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The brachium of the inferior colliculus connects the auditory relay to which thalamic nucleus?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lateral geniculate body</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The lateral geniculate body is the visual relay nucleus. It receives input from the superior colliculus via the brachium of the superior colliculus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial geniculate body</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The inferior colliculus relays auditory information to the medial geniculate body. A useful mnemonic: Medial = Music (auditory), Lateral = Light (visual).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ventral posterolateral nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The VPL relays somatosensory information (touch, pain, proprioception) from the body to the cortex. It is not part of the auditory pathway.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anterior thalamic nucleus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The anterior thalamic nucleus is part of the Papez circuit involved in memory and emotion, not auditory processing.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the brachia as bridges: inferior colliculus → medial geniculate body (auditory), and superior colliculus → lateral geniculate body (visual)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The inferior colliculus is the principal midbrain auditory relay. Its brachium carries fibres to the medial geniculate body, which then projects to the auditory cortex."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
