          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient presents with ipsilateral third nerve palsy and contralateral involunt</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient presents with ipsilateral third nerve palsy and contralateral involuntary movements (tremor, chorea) but NO limb weakness. Which midbrain structure is most likely damaged?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cerebral peduncle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A cerebral peduncle lesion causes Weber syndrome — ipsilateral CN III palsy with contralateral upper motor neuron hemiplegia, because the corticospinal tract is damaged.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dorsal midbrain (tectum)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Dorsal midbrain compression produces Parinaud syndrome — upgaze palsy, convergence-retraction nystagmus, and light-near dissociation. There is no CN III palsy in Parinaud syndrome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Red nucleus in the tegmentum</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. This is Benedikt syndrome. The tegmental lesion damages CN III fascicles (ipsilateral palsy) and the red nucleus (contralateral involuntary movements), while sparing the ventrally located corticospinal tract.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Substantia nigra</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Substantia nigra degeneration produces parkinsonian features (resting tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia) — a chronic neurodegenerative picture, not an acute crossed brainstem syndrome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key distinction: Weber = peduncle (hemiplegia), Benedikt = tegmentum (involuntary movements), Parinaud = tectum (upgaze palsy). All three share different combinations of findings based on which midbrain layer is affected."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Benedikt syndrome localises to the midbrain tegmentum. The red nucleus receives cerebellar input; its destruction releases contralateral involuntary movements while sparing the peduncle (no hemiplegia)."
                }
              ],
